      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 6-month-old boy begins experiencing vomiting, night sweats, and tremors after the introduction of fruit juices into his diet during weaning. Physical examination reveals significant hepatomegaly. Urine tests are positive for reducing sugars but negative for glucose. Which enzyme deficiency is most likely responsible for these symptoms? </span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5690381",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30025,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C) Aldolase B</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The above symptoms are suggestive of <strong>hereditary fructose intolerance (AR inheritance),</strong> due to <strong>deficiency of aldolase B.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Defect </strong>in <strong>aldolase-B</strong> &rarr; <strong>fructose-1-phosphate</strong> cannot be metabolized further &rarr; accumulation of <strong>fructose-1-phosphate</strong> will <strong>inhibit glycogen phosphorylase </strong>&rarr; accumulation of<strong> glycogen in liver </strong>and associated <strong>hypoglycemia.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">C/F-<strong> Vomiting, loss of appetite, failure to thrive, hepatomegaly and jaundice</strong>. These symptoms are manifested when <strong>sucrose (containing fructose)</strong> is introduced in the<strong> diet of infants (6 months of age).</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Diagnosis: Fructose</strong> is<strong> excreted in urine</strong> and urine gives<strong> positive Benedict&rsquo;s test.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Treatment: Withdrawal of fructose </strong>from the <strong>diet </strong>will relieve the symptoms.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<u>Explanation:</u></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A.&nbsp; Galactokinase:&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Deficiency </strong>in <strong>galactokinase</strong> leads to <strong>galactosemia type 2,</strong> which primarily results in <strong>cataract formation </strong>but <strong>does not</strong> typically cause <strong>severe hypoglycemia or hepatomegaly</strong> in response to fructose ingestion.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. Fructokinase:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong> Fructokinase deficiency </strong>leads to essential<strong> fructosuria,</strong> a <strong>benign</strong> condition characterized by the <strong>excretion of</strong> <strong>fructose</strong> in the<strong> urine</strong> <strong>without </strong>serious metabolic disturbances or clinical symptoms.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. &beta;-Galactosidase:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Deficiency in &beta;-galactosidase</strong> leads to<strong> GM1 gangliosidosis or galactosialidosis</strong>, which involve <strong>neurological symptoms</strong> and <strong>developmental delays</strong>, but <strong>not </strong>the specific reaction to <strong>fructose ingestion</strong> as described.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Hereditary Fructose Intolerance (HFI) </strong>is a condition resulting from <strong>aldolase B deficiency</strong>, characterized by <strong>adverse reactions</strong> to <strong>fructose ingestion,</strong> such as <strong>hypoglycemia, hepatomegaly, and metabolic disturbances.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Harper 30/e: p 155, 202, 205.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
