      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">A 4-year-old boy experiences headache, dizziness, weakness, and knee joint tenderness after consuming sugarcane juice. Following a diagnosis of Hereditary Fructose Intolerance (HFI), which of the following statements about HFI is FALSE?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q7292949",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30023,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. C. Hyperglycaemia</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Hyperglycaemia:</strong></span><br><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>False.</strong> The opposite is true—patients experience <strong>hypoglycemia</strong> because of inhibited glucose release from glycogen.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Explanation:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Hereditary Fructose Intolerance (HFI)</strong> is caused by a <strong>deficiency of aldolase B,</strong> the enzyme that cleaves <strong>fructose 1-phosphate into dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP) and glyceraldehyde.</strong></span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">In HFI:</span><ul style=\"list-style-type:circle;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Fructose 1-phosphate accumulates</strong> in tissues (especially the liver and&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;kidneys)leading to:</span><ul style=\"list-style-type:square;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Inhibition of glycogenolysis&nbsp;</strong></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Resulting in <strong>hypoglycemia (low blood sugar),</strong> especially after ingestion of fructose, sucrose, or sorbitol.</span></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Clinical findings:</strong></span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Hypoglycemia, vomiting, lethargy, abdominal pain after fructose intake.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Long-term exposure can cause <strong>hepatomegaly, liver dysfunction, and renal involvement.</strong></span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Other Options:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A. Deficiency of aldolase B:</strong></span><br><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>True.</strong> This is the fundamental enzymatic defect in HFI.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Accumulation of fructose 1-phosphate in tissues:</strong></span><br><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>True.</strong> This is the hallmark of the disease and leads to metabolic blockages.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D. Liver and kidneys are involved:</strong></span><br><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>True.</strong> These organs are significantly affected due to accumulation of fructose 1-phosphate and its toxic effects.</span></li></ul><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>&nbsp;</u></strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Biochemical defect in Hereditary Fructose Intolerance</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Deficiency of Fructose-1,6-Bisphosphate Aldolase (Aldolase B)</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Deficiency of this enzyme → causes accumulation of fructose-1-phosphate → severe toxic symptoms when a patient is exposed to fructose.&nbsp;</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Clinical manifestations</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Patients with HFI are asymptomatic until fructose or sucrose is ingested (usually from fruit, fruit juice, or sweetened cereal).</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Symptoms may occur early in life, soon after weaning formulas containing these sugars are introduced into the diet.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Early clinical manifestations include jaundice, hepatomegaly, vomiting, lethargy, irritability, convulsions and hypoglycaemia. &nbsp;</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ref</strong>: Vasudevan 9/e: p 138.</span></p>",
      "correct_choice_id": 25723,
