      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">An Infant diagnosed with Hereditary Fructose Intolerance (HFI) presents with vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal pain, and hypoglycemia upon attempting weaning. Following a positive IV fructose tolerance test, dietary restriction of fructose is advised. Considering the metabolic pathway affected in HFI, which of the following substances should be restricted in the neonate's diet?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q9363049",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30024,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. D) Sucrose&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D:</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Hereditary fructose intolerance (Fructosemia) is due to a deficiency of aldolase B, which is found in liver, small intestine, and kidney.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">It requires a strict dietary control of fructose (fruit sugar) and sucrose (table sugar).</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">As sucrose is a disaccharide made of fructose and glucose, it is restricted.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Other Options:</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A.&nbsp; Galactose</strong>: is a monosaccharide that is metabolized normally in this condition.&nbsp; Metabolic disorders associated with galactose metabolism&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Glucose</strong>: is metabolized normally in fructosemia.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Lactose</strong>: is a disaccharide composed of galactose + glucose, should be restricted in Classical Galactosemia and in lactose intolerance.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">In Infants with Hereditary Fructose Intolerance (HFI), dietary restriction of sucrose is crucial due to its breakdown into glucose and fructose, the latter of which cannot be metabolized due to aldolase B deficiency, leading to toxic metabolite buildup and hypoglycemia. Other sugars like galactose, glucose, and lactose, which do not directly contribute to these metabolic issues, do not need to be restricted unless other specific metabolic disorders are present.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Ref: Harper 30/e:&nbsp; p 202, 205.</span></p>",
      "correct_choice_id": 25604,
