      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) Deficiency of aldolase B</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Fructosuria</strong> is typically caused by a<strong> deficiency in the enzyme fructokinase, not</strong> <strong>aldolase B. </strong>This condition leads to the <strong>excretion </strong>of <strong>fructose in the urine</strong> because the <strong>body cannot</strong> effectively <strong>metabolize fructose into fructose-1-phosphate </strong>in the <strong>liver. </strong>As a result, <strong>fructose accumulates </strong>in the<strong> blood </strong>and is <strong>excreted in the urine. </strong>The condition is indeed rare and usually benign, and because <strong>fructose</strong> is a <strong>reducing sugar</strong>, it can produce a <strong>positive result </strong>on a <strong>Benedict&#39;s test, </strong>which tests for the<strong> presence of reducing sugars</strong> in the <strong>urine.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<u>Explanation:</u></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B.&nbsp; Excretes fructose in urine:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> This is <strong>true</strong> for fructosuria due to the <strong>inability to metabolize fructose</strong> effectively.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Rare incidence:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Fructosuria </strong>is indeed a rare condition, given the <strong>specific enzyme deficiency</strong> required for its manifestation.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Positive Benedict&rsquo;s test:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Fructose is a <strong>reducing sugar,</strong> which means it will <strong>react with Benedict&rsquo;s reagent </strong>to produce a <strong>color</strong> <strong>change</strong>, indicating a <strong>positive test result.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">This is a <strong>benign metabolic defect</strong> due to <strong>defect/deficiency of fructokinase.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Incidence is<strong> 1 in 130,000 births.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">There is<strong> excretion of fructose</strong> in urine. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Urine gives<strong> positive Benedict&rsquo;s and Seliwanoff&rsquo;s tests. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Vasudevan 9/e: P 138.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
